Based on recent interview with Singapore PM, analyze how Singapore will deepen bilateral ties and economic relations with China in coming years, and craft hypotheses about how this will impact Singapore.

---

Based on the provided transcript, here is a reconstruction of the interview narrative.

### Introduction and Leadership Transition

**Zou Yun:** Mr. Prime Minister, good morning to you and thank you for joining us on Leaders Talk. It has been just over a year since you assumed office as the Prime Minister of Singapore and nearly a month since your cabinet was sworn in. So how has this transition into the role been for you and the responsibilities that come with leading a nation?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** It's a big job with significant responsibilities. There's nothing that really prepares you for this, and even for someone like me, I've been in government for a long time. I've been in the civil service for nearly 15 years and in politics for about 14 years, so nearly 30 years of experience. Still, coming into a job like this, there is still a lot to learn and adapt and adjust to. But fortunately, I have a strong team of ministers and Members of Parliament supporting me, and so it has been a smooth transition, both in the government and in the leadership of the People's Action Party. I led the party into our general elections, and I am very grateful that Singaporeans gave me a clear mandate to lead for another term.

### Upcoming Visit to China and Bilateral Relations

**Zou Yun:** Prime Minister Wong, you've been to China many times before, but you are going to embark on your very first official trip to China as the Prime Minister of Singapore next week. So what different expectations do you have for this trip, and what will be the key priorities guiding your agenda?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** Well, I made it a point to visit China almost every year since entering politics because it's useful to visit regularly to interact, exchange notes with my counterparts, and to get a sense of how China is moving and transforming. I've always had good visits; I've always had good exchanges and meetings with my counterparts. As you say, this time will be a different occasion. It's more special this time because it's my first visit in my capacity as Prime Minister.

I would look forward to achieving several objectives: first, to just establish closer ties with Chinese leaders, especially with President Xi Jinping and Premier Li Qiang. Second, to reaffirm our shared commitment to enhancing our bilateral cooperation, especially as we mark the 35th anniversary of diplomatic ties this year. And then, of course, thirdly, to discuss the wider regional and global developments that we are all confronting during this challenging period and to see how we can continue working together to strengthen multilateralism and the rules-based global order.

**Zou Yun:** You met with Chinese President Xi Jinping last November on the sidelines of the APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting. What's your impression and also some of the major takeaways from your meeting with President Xi? And as you just mentioned, you will be scheduled to meet President Xi again. What are some of the major topics that you hope to touch upon during this meeting?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** We had a short but productive meeting at the sidelines of APEC last year, my first time in fact as Prime Minister at that time. We discussed our bilateral cooperation, we discussed cooperation in regional platforms like APEC and how we can take this forward. And I said to the President at that time that I would be visiting China next year—that was in 2024, I said next year in 2025—when we mark the 35th anniversary of diplomatic ties. So I'm doing so right after the elections, at the soonest possible opportunity to visit China now, and I hope to be able to meet him again.

**Zou Yun:** And just now you mentioned that your visit this time coincides with the 35th anniversary of diplomatic relations between our two nations. So how do you interpret this partnership, which was upgraded in 2023, now termed as an "all-round, high-quality, future-oriented partnership," and what is your vision towards the future trajectory of it?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** China and Singapore have a very close and steadfast partnership. It's a partnership that's built on mutual trust, respect, and understanding. It started with our founding Prime Minister, Mr. Lee Kuan Yew, and Mr. Deng Xiaoping, and successive Prime Ministers of Singapore since then have built on that strong foundation to establish close rapport and trust with their Chinese counterparts. So I hope to do the same in my visit with Chinese leaders, especially with President Xi and Premier Li. And I think the close ties at the leadership level set the tone for the overall relationship.

We have an apex body called the JCBC, the Joint Council for Bilateral Cooperation, that oversees the many multifaceted and comprehensive projects we have with one another. I used to be the Singapore co-chair of the JCBC. In fact, the JCBC meets every year. Each time they meet, the agenda keeps growing because there are so many things to discuss. But it's not just the number of projects, because in the spirit of our partnership, we are pursuing projects that are all-round or comprehensive, that are high in quality, and are also future-oriented. And so these are the guideposts that will shape our cooperation in the future. And with the close partnership we have, I am optimistic that the future of our cooperation is bright and there are many more things we can do together.

### Reflections on China's Development

**Zou Yun:** As you just raised, you've been to China many times, to cities including Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Chongqing, etc. So what are some of the major changes and transformations you have witnessed through all those years in terms of China's development and modernization that you think are inspirational to you in governing a nation?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** The transformation and success of China, I feel, is nothing short of an economic miracle. Because in the last 20 or so years when I've been visiting China regularly, even as a civil servant and then later as a politician, across so many different Chinese cities—not just your Beijing and Shanghai, but even in a city like Chengdu and other cities—you can see transformation happening. You can see the determination and the drive of the Chinese people to move forward, and you can see lives getting better and improving. So it's a remarkable change, and I continue to wish China every success in its ongoing transformation and modernization efforts.

**Zou Yun:** And you recently made the remark that "never bet on the decline of China." So what are the key factors that underpin your confidence? And has China's recent economic performance, especially amidst the global headwinds, reinforced your belief in its long-term resilience and also potential?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** Well, first of all, is what I've just described: it's the track record of success, remarkable success. Of course, you can say past performance does not predict future performance, but still, it's a very impressive track record which gives one confidence. But a second factor is that I've interacted so many times with Chinese leaders at all levels—the mayors, the party secretaries, the governors, and of course the leaders at the center in Beijing—and I've always been impressed by the high level of competence, by their deep mastery of issues. They understand the challenges, they are focused on resolving the challenges and problems that China faces.

But it's more than just competence and mastery; it's also a willingness to listen and to be open-minded about finding better solutions. Because governments never get everything right; it's impossible. Governments will make mistakes from time to time. What distinguishes a high-quality system is the ability to reflect, learn, and keep on improving and doing better. And I see that in the Chinese system. But the biggest reason, the most important reason why I have confidence in China, is because of the people of China. It's because of their tremendous ingenuity and resourcefulness, the deep drive to succeed, to strive and work hard. And that gives me confidence that China will continue to have a good future ahead.

### Global Challenges and Multilateralism

**Zou Yun:** You'll be attending the Annual Meeting of the New Champions, which will take place in Tianjin this year, also known as Summer Davos. So what will be the key messages that you hope to deliver there, especially with this global context, with the world now going through choppy waters filled with so many different challenges?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** We are in the midst of a profound global change. So my message at Tianjin will be the importance of upholding a rules-based multilateral order. Because without rules, without long-standing norms of cooperation, countries everywhere will be worse off. Small countries like Singapore, of course, are very concerned because we have limited bargaining power and we risk being sidelined and squeezed by the bigger powers. But I think big countries will be impacted too, because if we end up in a world that's more fragmented, where there's deep suspicion and mistrust of one another, this will be a world with great uncertainty and volatility. And you will have slower growth and higher inflation in the global economy, which means all countries will suffer, and our people at the end of the day will be the ones facing the impact. So we have to do something about this. Of course, multilateralism today is not perfect. There are things that can be improved, but our response should not be to abandon the multilateral system. Our response should be to reform, change, improve, and make the system work better for the benefit of all countries.

**Zou Yun:** Given the challenges you just touched upon—the tensions in trade, the anti-globalization trend, various geopolitical risks, and so many different pressing issues faced by the world—what is your top concern for Singapore from your perspective?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** Well, we know that from Singapore's perspective, we are small, we are an open economy, we rely heavily on trade. So this new external environment will make it less hospitable for us to continue flourishing. So we have to find ways to navigate the external environment carefully. But I think despite the changes that we see around us, trade will still continue. Countries do want to be more self-sufficient in this new environment, but it's not possible for any single country to do everything themselves.

**Zou Yun:** But talking about trade, you've recently described the tariffs imposed by the Trump administration as a "seismic change in the global order," suggesting the era of free trade is over. Given what you have just mentioned, Singapore's heavy reliance on global trade, what are the specific plans or the priorities for your government to navigate through the shifts and also the pressure in the global trading system?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** As I mentioned just now, the era of free trade or the era that we are familiar with may be over, but trade will still continue. Different configurations, different supply chains. We will try to be competitive, we will try to stay relevant, but at the same time, we will work with like-minded countries to uphold free trade and to uphold a rules-based trading system. And we are doing this with our neighbors in ASEAN. So within ASEAN, we are accelerating our integration, bringing down trade and non-trade barriers so that we can make ASEAN a more integrated community, more competitive, more attractive for investors. We are doing this with partners in Asia like China, India, Japan, South Korea, for example, working closely with all the key players in Asia. But we are also pursuing this with countries outside of Asia, like the EU, Latin America, Africa, for example. And some of these are countries we are not so familiar with, but we think we should now make an extra effort to establish closer links with them. We are also strengthening our cooperation in regional platforms like RCEP and CPTPP, and we are finding ways to establish new linkages across different platforms, for example, between ASEAN and other groupings. So these are all different areas we are exploring. I believe in every crisis, there will always be opportunities, and so we are finding ways to seize new opportunities for ourselves and for other countries.

**Zou Yun:** Just like the Chinese phrase "wēijī."

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** So opportunities always come with... we may speak English, but we are very Asian in our thinking.

### Deepening China-Singapore Cooperation

**Zou Yun:** Speaking of regional and global cooperation, China and ASEAN about a month ago have announced the conclusion of negotiations on Version 3.0 of the FTA, with the aim to be signed by year-end. So how do you interpret the significance of this upgraded protocol, especially in this global context of rising protectionism and uncertainties?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** It's a very important upgrade, and Singapore fully supports it. It's in line with the spirit of what I said just now, that amidst the pressures of protectionism and trade barriers, Singapore will want to work closely with ASEAN and other like-minded countries to continue to uphold free trade and a rules-based trading system. So in that spirit, we fully support the upgrade to the China-ASEAN FTA. We hope this can be signed at the coming ASEAN-China Summit in October and that the new upgrade will come into force soon after that.

**Zou Yun:** Over the years, China and Singapore have established three major government-to-government projects in Suzhou, Tianjin, and Chongqing, and also state-level bilateral cooperation projects such as the Guangzhou Knowledge City. Mr. Prime Minister, do you envision, for instance, introducing a new project during your term, or what are some of the new areas of cooperation do you expect apart from these existing initiatives?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** I would first clarify that these existing initiatives are not simply projects that are completed and then we've turned the page and we move on to something else. They are developing and growing; they are work in progress. In fact, they are platforms. The G2G, the government-to-government initiatives that we have, are platforms for wider cooperation.

To illustrate, the Suzhou Industrial Park, which was our first government-to-government cooperation, was very successful, and now we recently marked the 30th anniversary of the Suzhou Industrial Park. And now we're looking at a new frontier for cooperation, where the cooperation may be wider, not just between the government entities but with a wider ecosystem of players. Or take another example of Tianjin Eco-City. Yes, it started as a barren wasteland, and the vision was to transform this place into a place for eco-living, green living. We've achieved that vision, and recently we marked the 15th anniversary of the Tianjin Eco-City. And now we are saying, let's look ahead, have a new chapter, and think about how the Tianjin project can be a model for high-quality green development and sustainable growth for China.

So in each of these projects, we are constantly finding new ways to cooperate. At the same time, beyond these existing platforms, we are always open to new ideas, and we are continuing to discuss new possibilities for cooperation, including in areas like low-carbon green energy, digital economy, and biomedical sciences. So the point is, the cooperation between our two countries, because of the close partnership, is never static. It never stands still. We are always upgrading, improving, trying to find new opportunities to cooperate and to be responsive to the needs of our times. That's the spirit of our cooperation. That's why I'm so confident that we can continue to do more together.

### The Geopolitical Landscape

**Zou Yun:** The world is now going through so many major challenges, the challenges unseen in a century. So what is your reading, your evaluation of the current global scene in terms of the geopolitical risks, those uncertainties that we're faced with?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** We are in the midst of a very messy and unpredictable transition. We are in a state of flux, and it will take time before we find a new equilibrium. I think the new order will be shaped eventually by not just a single superpower but by all countries, large and small, by the actions and choices of all countries, big and small. And this will take time. In the meantime, we are in this period of transition, very unpredictable, very chaotic, and potentially very dangerous as well. Because during this period, without clear global leadership and coordination, there are many things that can go wrong in this world. So I think what's important for all of us, countries everywhere, is to recognize the dangers that we are in, for all of us to do our part to manage geopolitical tensions and rivalry carefully in order to minimize the risk of conflict and war, for us to find ways to get countries to still work together and find win-win cooperation, especially in areas of shared interest. And then step by step, we can all work together to lay the groundwork for a new and more stable global order that may emerge in the years ahead. It will take time, but we should all do our part to shape this new global order.

**Zou Yun:** But in this time of transition, imposing heavy tariffs on so many different countries around the world might not be the proper solution, right?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** We don't believe it is. The administration reflects a growing sentiment amongst the American people that they are paying too high a price to be the world's policeman, to underwrite the global system, and they have not benefited. In fact, we believe America has benefited. It has benefited if America were to take an enlightened self-interest, not just a very narrow perspective of its interest, but a wider view of its interest. This system has benefited America too.

### 4G Leadership and Personal Reflections

**Zou Yun:** Back here in Singapore, you are referred to as the leader of 4G, the fourth generation of political leadership. So what core values do you believe define the governing style of 4G leaders?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** The leadership we have now will continue to uphold the core values of the People's Action Party. These values will never change: the values of incorruptibility, meritocracy, multi-racialism—because we are a diverse society—and self-reliance. So these core values will continue to be values that my team and I will uphold in governing Singapore. But at the same time, our leadership approach will be different. Every leader has to be himself; you cannot pretend to be someone else. My approach is to be open, to listen to different views and suggestions, even if they are views which are different from mine. I would like to listen to them. I would like to engage widely and involve as many people as possible. But at the end of the day, the government must decide, must come to a decision.

**Zou Yun:** What kind of narrative do 4G leaders aspire to create, especially in light of the remark you made that "the best chapters of Singapore's story are yet to be written"?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** We hope we can continue to keep Singapore special, exceptional, a shining red dot. A shining little red dot that will continue to add value to the world and ensure that everyone in Singapore can continue to achieve better lives.

**Zou Yun:** What do you mean by a "shining red dot"? It is small but is very evident and it's shining, or what?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** It's a little red dot because that's the, I suppose, slogan that we have for ourselves. Yes, because we are a small country. But shining... history has never been kind to small countries. You look at the long arc of history, small countries find it very hard to survive. Singapore has defied the odds for 60 years. This is 60 years of independence this year. We will try to continue defying the odds of history and keep Singapore special.

**Zou Yun:** A very unique experience in your career is serving as the Principal Private Secretary to the then Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong from 2005 to 2008. So what are some of the major lessons or the biggest source of inspiration that you gained from working very closely with Senior Minister Lee?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** I was always struck by how devoted he was to Singapore, to the country, and how obsessed he was every single day, thinking about how to keep Singapore going. Because as I said just now, we feel the vulnerabilities more as a small country. Big countries, you may feel, you know, there are resources, you've got wealth, you've got many things you can rely on. But as a small country, we always feel we are vulnerable. We take nothing for granted. And I was always struck by how obsessed he was. So now that the leadership baton has been passed to me, this has become my obsession. And I'll do everything in my power, together with my teammates, to keep Singapore moving forward.

**Zou Yun:** Mr. Prime Minister, when you first emerged as the new leader of the nation, I don't know whether you have noticed that if you take a closer look at the headlines at that time about media coverage of you, there is sometimes a phrase that is frequently used. Do you know what it is?

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** I have no idea. There are many phrases.

**Zou Yun:** Sometimes it's "guitar-playing prime minister" or "guitar-wielding prime minister." We heard it's actually a guitar from your father, a gift when you were a child, that sparked your passion for music and playing guitar.

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** Well, I started playing at a very young age, maybe eight years old or something like that. But I never had formal lessons; I was self-taught.

**Zou Yun:** Yes. So I don't claim to play very well at all.

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** That's very modest because we saw some of the videos.

**Zou Yun:** I enjoy doing it. I find that music helps to break barriers, it helps to bring people together, and so I enjoy doing it. But for me personally, I just find it's a good way to unwind, to de-stress. Especially doing a job like this, you do need outlets to relax from time to time.

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** Is there a go-to Chinese song that you really enjoyed playing with your guitar? We're just wondering.

**Zou Yun:** I have played a number of Chinese songs. For example, "月亮代表我的心" (The Moon Represents My Heart) is one song that I would play in my constituency.

**Prime Minister Lawrence Wong:** Mr. Prime Minister, thank you so much for sharing with us your time and also your insightful views. It's greatly appreciated.

**Zou Yun:** Thank you very much.

### 1  Key Signals from PM Wong’s Interview  
| Signal | Implication for Singapore-China Relations |
|---|---|
| **Leadership chemistry & 35th-anniversary optics** – PM Wong is prioritising an early trip to Beijing/Tianjin and expects regular contact with President Xi and Premier Li. | High-level access lowers coordination costs, lets both sides “dial up” new initiatives quickly, and keeps the **Joint Council for Bilateral Cooperation (JCBC)** politically salient. |
| **Partnership framing – “all-round, high-quality, future-oriented”** | Both capitals now benchmark cooperation not by quantity of projects but by strategic relevance (digital, green, supply-chain security) and replication value for third markets. |
| **Rules-based multilateralism & ASEAN centrality** | Singapore wants deeper China ties *without* becoming a geopolitical appendage. Anchoring deals in ASEAN frameworks (e.g., CAFTA 3.0) gives Singapore political cover and a bigger market to offer China. |
| **Acknowledgement that the “free-trade era” is over** | Expect Singapore to hedge by embedding China links inside many overlapping trade, digital-trade and sustainability agreements—so if one corridor closes, others remain open. |

### 2  Likely Avenues for Deepening Ties

| **1. | **5. Financial intermediation & capital flows** | Singapore has been China’s largest foreign investor since 2013; China is Singapore’s top merchandise-trade partner (S$170 bn in 2024) citeturn2search0turn1search2 | Broaden the RMB Liquidity Facility with MAS; explore south-bound Bond Connect listing Chinese corporate sustainability bonds in Singapore. |
| **6. People-to-people & R&D links** | Post-COVID travel rebound; rising Chinese enrolment in Singaporean universities. | Singapore–China Co-Innovation Fund (proposed) to co-finance AI, biotech and ag-tech start-ups, each with an R&D node in the other country. |

### 3  Hypotheses on Impact to Singapore  

| # | Hypothesis | Rationale & Indicators to Watch |
|---|---|---|
| **H1 – Trade uplift of 15-20 % by 2030** | CAFTA 3.0 lowers non-tariff barriers in digital services and green goods across a US$1 tn China-ASEAN corridor. Even a modest elasticity (0.4) on the current S$170 bn merchandise base implies **S$10-15 bn extra annual trade** for Singapore by 2030. Track: CAFTA utilisation rates; Tuas port TEUs bound for China. |
| **H2 – Surge in Chinese capital routed via Singapore** | Upgraded CSFTA grants easier market access for Singaporean financial products; Singapore’s rule-of-law brand provides a regulatory “middle ground” for Chinese firms raising USD or RMB outside the mainland. Expect **double-digit growth in RMB settlements and green-bond listings on SGX**. Track: MAS RMB clearing volume, SGX bond issuance data. |
| **H3 – Green-tech & digital-services clusters add 20 000–30 000 skilled jobs** | Joint projects (Eco-City 2.0, hydrogen pilots, med-tech parks) require engineers, data scientists and compliance specialists. Monitor: EDB investments in cleantech, digital-trade start-up employment. |
| **H4 – Greater concentration risk to China economic cycle** | If China’s structural slowdown persists (<4 % GDP growth), sectors tightly coupled to Chinese demand (petrochemicals, tourism retail) face earnings volatility. Singapore’s diversification into EU/India may blunt but not remove this exposure. Watch: share of China in non-oil domestic exports (NODX). |
| **H5 – Geopolitical balancing costs rise** | Deep entanglement increases the probability of US export-control or secondary-sanction pressure on firms operating in dual-use tech (AI chips, quantum). Compliance overheads and the need for “two-track” supply chains could erode some efficiency gains. Indicators: number of Singapore companies seeking US export-licence waivers; MAS guidance on sanctions. |
| **H6 – Domestic social pressures from talent inflows** | More Chinese professionals may tighten housing and schooling bottlenecks, reigniting public concern over immigration. The government’s tighter Employment Pass framework (COMPASS) will be a critical valve. Track: EP approvals by nationality; private-home rental index. |

### 4  Risk-Adjusted Outlook & Mitigation  

| Risk | Likelihood | Mitigation Strategy Already Signalled |
|---|---|---|
| US-China tariff/technology escalations spill over (e.g., ICT blacklist) | **Medium–high** | Singapore embeds China deals in multilateral or ASEAN settings, giving them political legitimacy; promotes digital-standards interoperability to avoid tech bifurcation. |
| China growth undershoots >2 ppt for several years | **Medium** | Expand ties with India, GCC and Africa concurrently; accelerate services exports (finance, logistics, education) less dependent on China’s domestic demand. |
| Domestic backlash to rapid foreign-talent inflow | **Medium** | PM Wong’s “listening leadership” + progressive wage moves; COMPASS and tighter S-Pass quotas to pace inflows. |
| Green-tech hype fails to commercialise | **Low–medium** | Pilot projects are structured as modular “sandbox” trials (Eco-City upgrades, hydrogen bunkering) to cap sunk costs if technologies stall. |

### 5  Strategic Take-aways  

1. **Incremental but relentless** – Singapore’s model is evolutionary: take an existing platform, upgrade, replicate. Expect *many* small, high-quality announcements rather than one flagship megaproject.  
2. **Hub-and-spoke resilience** – By embedding Chinese links inside broader ASEAN, RCEP and digital frameworks, Singapore keeps optionality if great-power rivalry worsens.  
3. **Shift from goods to intangibles** – The next growth engine is data, algorithms, and green intellectual property, not container-ship tonnage. Singapore’s comparative advantage is in *rules, trust and finance* rather than scale.  
4. **Domestic governance matters** – Success hinges on managing social sentiment and maintaining a neutral foreign-policy brand. Without this, economic gains could erode political capital.  

**Bottom line:**  If present trends continue, deeper Sino-Singapore economic integration will likely lift trade and green-digital investment, cement Singapore’s status as *ASEAN’s node for China’s outward strategy*, and create high-skill jobs.  The main strategic challenge will be balancing this growth against geopolitical volatility and domestic capacity constraints—an equation that PM Wong’s administration appears keenly aware of and already engineering safeguards for.

entries.snippet: Singapore's central bank, the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS), has announced an increased collaboration with China's People's Bank to enhance green finance initiatives. This includes developing a decarbonization ratings platform and creating a green finance corridor between the two nations. The collaboration aims to facilitate green finance flows and establish a taxonomy for green bonds and loans by the end of the year. Concurrently, MAS plans to issue sovereign green bonds worth up to S$2.5 billion (US$1.56 billion) with a 30-year tenure for environmental projects, part of Singapore's goal to issue up to S$35 billion in green bonds by 2030. The green finance strategy involves partnerships like that with China International Capital to streamline the issuance of green panda bonds. This effort aims to boost funding for environmentally sustainable projects, as sovereign bonds are increasingly dominating the green bond market, with significant growth observed in recent years.

entries.title: Which countries can Chinese passport holders visit without a visa?
entries.snippet: Since reopening its borders in 2023, China has established various visa waiver agreements to facilitate the travel of its citizens and attract foreign tourists. Chinese passport holders can visit countries such as Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore, Germany, France, Spain, the Netherlands, and Italy without a visa for a specified period. Mutual visa exemption agreements include countries predominantly in Asia, some in Europe, the Americas, Africa, and Oceania. For example, Thailand, Singapore, Kazakhstan, UAE, Qatar, Maldives, Armenia, Albania, Belarus, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Serbia, San Marino, Barbados, Bahamas, Ecuador, Dominica, Grenada, Suriname, Mauritius, Seychelles, Fiji, and Tonga. Several countries and regions offer unilateral visa-free access, including Antigua and Barbuda, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Haiti, Saint Lucia, Jamaica, Oman, South Korea's Jeju Island, Uzbekistan, Iran, Phu Quoc Island in Vietnam, Georgia, Micronesia, Niue, Samoa, French Polynesia, Kiribati, Gabon, Morocco, Mozambique, Tunisia, Zambia, Angola, and Benin. Moreover, over 40 countries allow Chinese passport holders to obtain visas on arrival, including Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, Madagascar, Bolivia, Cook Islands, Palau, and Egypt. Transit visa exemptions are available in over 40 countries, including Austria, Poland, Switzerland, Cyprus, Slovakia, Hungary, and Italy.

Below is a forward-looking briefing on what to watch for during Prime Minister Lawrence Wong’s 22- 26 June visit to Beijing and Tianjin, distilled from the official schedule, recent bilateral initiatives and commentary by analysts. --- ## 1 Official programme at a glance | Day | City | Confirmed engagements* | |-----|------|------------------------| | 22 Jun (Sun) | **Beijing** | Arrival; welcome ceremony & banquet hosted by Premier Li Qiang. | | 23 Jun (Mon) | Beijing | Separate meetings with President Xi Jinping and NPC Chairman Zhao Leji; reception with Singaporeans in Beijing. | | 24 Jun (Tue) | Beijing → Tianjin | Bilateral talks continue in the morning; travel to Tianjin. | | 25 Jun (Wed) | **Tianjin** | Keynote dialogue with WEF President Børge Brende at Summer Davos (“Entrepreneurship for a New Era”); official dinner for attending leaders. | | 26 Jun (Thu) | Tianjin | Site visit linked to the Tianjin Eco-City/Green-Digital Shipping Corridor; departure. | \*Drawn from the PMO release and Chinese MFA briefing. citeturn1view0turn20view0 The delegation includes Foreign Minister Vivian Balakrishnan, Trade-Relations Minister Grace Fu and Acting Transport Minister Jeffrey Siow, signalling an agenda heavy on economic, sustainability and connectivity issues. citeturn1view0 --- ## 2 Likely deliverables & announcements | Domain | Why it matters | What to look for | |--------|----------------|------------------| | **A. 35th-anniversary Joint Statement** | Symbolic capstone for the *“all-round, high-quality, future-oriented partnership”* minted in 2023. | Language reaffirming mutual **“strategic trust”** and pledging to “operationalise” new FTA chapters on the digital and green economy. | | **B. China-ASEAN FTA 3.0 (CAFTA-3.0)** | Negotiations were fully concluded in May; Singapore is a lead advocate. citeturn19view0 | A commitment by both leaders to sign the protocol at the ASEAN–China Summit in Oct 2025 and begin domestic ratification. | | **C. Green-finance corridor** | The MAS-PBoC Green Finance Taskforce has already mapped taxonomies and piloted panda-bond issuance. citeturn18view0 | • Joint communique announcing **taxonomy interoperability** completion by year-end.
• Expansion of the bond “Green Corridor” to cover transition loans and carbon-credit trading. | | **D. Digital-trade & data links** | Singapore’s TradeTrust and China’s customs blockchain are already interoperating in trial shipments. citeturn15search0 | MoU on a **“Trusted Cross-Border Data Pilot”** giving selected firms certainty on data localisation and AI-model governance. | | **E. Supply-chain connectivity** | The Tianjin green & digital shipping corridor now tests alternative fuels and smart-container tracking. citeturn17view0 | Road-map for scaling the corridor to include hydrogen/ammonia bunkering and electronic bills-of-lading acceptance at both ports. | | **F. People-to-people mobility** | A 30-day mutual visa-free regime is already in place. citeturn16search6 | Possible extension to *90-day multiple-entry* for business travellers and announcement of additional SIN-Beijing/Tianjin flights. | | **G. Multilateral messaging** | Both sides face rising U.S. tariff pressure and need external demand. citeturn4view0 | PM Wong’s Summer Davos speech likely pushes **rules-based multilateralism** and cautions against “weaponised tariffs” while inviting investment into ASEAN supply chains anchored in Singapore. | --- ## 3 Strategic signals to watch 1. **Tone of Xi–Wong remarks.** If President Xi positions Singapore as *ASEAN’s pivotal partner* in supply-chain security, expect faster regulatory clearance for Singapore firms in China’s services sector. 2. **References to the South China Sea or Middle East crises.** Any explicit language on de-escalation will hint at Beijing’s willingness to use Singapore as a diplomatic bridge. 3. **Follow-on ministerial tracks.** Presence of Trade-Relations and Transport ministers suggests quick scheduling of next-round JCBC and Maritime Cooperation dialogues to lock in technical details. 4. **Private-sector side-deals.** Watch for announcements by Temasek, CapitaLand or GIC in life-sciences parks, renewable-energy assets or RMB-denominated funds in Beijing-Tianjin-Hebei. --- ## 4 Plausible outcomes for Singapore | KPI | 12-month horizon | 3--5-year horizon | |-----|------------------|-------------------| | *Merchandise trade with China* | +3-4 % uplift from tariff cuts already embedded in CAFTA-3.0 chapters. | +15-20 % if digital-services commitments and rules-of-origin reforms are fully implemented. | | *Green-finance volumes via Singapore* | At least **S$3 bn** in new panda and sustainability-linked bonds routed through SGX. | Emergence of a **S$15-20 bn annual green-capital pipeline**, cementing Singapore as ASEAN’s RMB hub. | | *New economy jobs* | 2 000-3 000 roles (data-policy, carbon accounting, port tech) created by initial pilots. | 20 000-30 000 skilled positions across cleantech, fintech, AI governance and maritime innovation clusters. | | *Geopolitical risk* | Minimal in year one; deliverables are largely apolitical. | Rising exposure to U.S. export-control and sanctions regimes, demanding a “two-track” compliance strategy for Singapore firms. | --- ## 5 Bottom line Expect **concrete but measured** deliverables rather than a single headline-grabbing mega-project. The trip is calibrated to: * **Lock-in technical architecture** (green-finance, data, shipping corridors) that converts the upgraded partnership rhetoric into usable rules and platforms; * **Showcase Singapore’s convening power** at Summer Davos as a voice for middle powers defending open trade; * **Send markets a confidence signal on China’s economic trajectory** while giving Singaporean corporates preferential on-ramps into China’s green and digital sectors. If even half the anticipated MOUs reach implementation stage, Singapore secures new growth engines in finance, logistics and digital services—at the cost of deeper sensitivity to U.S.–China rivalry and the need for deft domestic management of talent inflows and strategic neutrality.
